{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535478"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:56:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:56:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15484"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15484"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.03,0.11,0.06,0.79]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61591"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8175"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47044"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2282"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"3773"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8082"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61591"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three days of progressive shortness of breath and pleuritic chest pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She recently completed a 12-hour international flight. On examination, she appears anxious. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 93% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her chest is clear to auscultation. Her calves are non-tender and non-swollen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements regarding pulmonary embolism assessment is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right ventricle to left ventricle diameter ratio \u003E0.9 indicates reduced mortality risk","Ventilation/perfusion scanning cannot detect chronic pulmonary thromboembolism","D-dimer testing alone can exclude pulmonary embolism","A negative ventilation/perfusion scan requires further imaging","A negative lower limb venous doppler ultrasound does not exclude pulmonary embolism"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a patient with risk factors and clinical features suggestive of pulmonary embolism (PE). Understanding the limitations and appropriate use of diagnostic tests is crucial for accurate diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA negative lower limb venous doppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E does not exclude PE as the clot may have completely embolised from the legs to the lungs, or may have formed in situ in the pulmonary vessels. Therefore, if clinical suspicion remains high, further imaging is warranted regardless of ultrasound findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Eright ventricle to left ventricle diameter ratio \u003E0.9 indicates reduced mortality risk\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In fact, this finding indicates right ventricular strain and is associated with increased mortality risk in acute PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentilation/perfusion scanning\u003C/strong\u003E can effectively detect both acute and chronic pulmonary thromboembolism. The statement suggesting it cannot detect chronic PE is incorrect. Chronic PE typically shows organised thrombi and associated perfusion defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED-dimer testing alone\u003C/strong\u003E cannot exclude PE. While a negative D-dimer in low-risk patients can help exclude PE, it must be interpreted in conjunction with clinical probability assessment tools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that a \u003Cstrong\u003Enegative ventilation/perfusion scan requires further imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. A normal V/Q scan (high-quality study reported as \u0027normal\u0027 or \u0027very low probability\u0027) effectively rules out clinically significant PE and does not require additional imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A negative leg ultrasound does not exclude pulmonary embolism as clots may have embolised completely or formed in situ.","Right ventricular strain (RV:LV ratio \u003E0.9) indicates severe pulmonary embolism with increased mortality risk.","Ventilation/perfusion scans use technetium-99m gas for ventilation and radiolabelled albumin for perfusion phases."],"references":["Toplis E, Mortimore G. The diagnosis and management of pulmonary embolism. Br J Nurs. 2020 Jan 9;29(1):22-26. doi: 10.12968/bjon.2020.29.1.22. PMID: 31917939","Shah IK, Merfeld JM, Chun J, Tak T. Pathophysiology and Management of Pulmonary Embolism. Int J Angiol. 2022 Sep 23;31(3):143-149. doi: 10.1055/s-0042-1756204. PMID: 36157092; PMCID: PMC9507564","Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47044"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15484"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47044"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T21:23:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T21:25:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8175"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61591"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","